Records indicate that in 1943 and 1944 volunteer defence groups conducted mortar shooting and training in the area.
Site declared air gunnery range from 1944 with ordnance thought to include bullets, rockets, cannon and practice bombs. Possible use by Army between 1940-1992 as a high explosive firing range.
Used by volunteer defence groups in 1943 for high explosive mortar and grenades, and anti-aircraft shell manufacturing facility. Possibly also used post WWII for army live firing exercises.

RAAF fighter/bomber, USAF heavy bomber and Dutch Maritime aircraft were based here using conventional armaments, conducted live firing practices using high explosive ordnance. Eighteen-pounder artillery guns were fired at land and seaward targets.
Field artillery group conducted conventional high explosive firing practices, including the firing of artillery concentrations, in the Narngulu area.

An artillery detachment was located on Cape Leveque for beach defence/anti-invasion duties in order to protect a RAAF radar station established on the cape. The guns were fired to seaward, and were probably fired at land based targets.

properties.general_location: 5 km S S E of Midland
properties.description: The area has been used as a rifle range since 1914. Searches have confirmed evidence that military activities on the range could have resulted in UXO.

properties.general_location: 75 km N N W of Perth
properties.description: Possible that RAAF high explosive bombing may have occurred near river mouth.

During WWII Army anti-aircraft unit was located in the vicinity of Derby. Live firing practices using high explosive ammunition occurred. RAAF fighter/bomber and bomber aircraft used Derby airstrip, and live firing and bombing practices occurred.
Gun emplacements along Fremantle coast with possible abandonment of ammunition on sites.

During WWII Army anti-aircraft unit was located in the vicinity of Derby. Live firing practices using high explosive ammunition occurred. RAAF fighter/bomber and bomber aircraft used Derby airstrip, and live firing and bombing practices occurred.

properties.general_location: 5 km S S E of Yanchep
properties.description: Extensive field assessment surveys carried out for all subdivision that has occurred in this area since late 2000. No evidence of high explosive ordnance has been found south of grid square 7302.

properties.general_location: 20 km N N W of Esperance
properties.description: During WWII high explosive ammunition was stored, tested, destroyed by controlled detonation and possibly dropped from aircraft for training purposes.  Volunteer defence groups also trained in the area.

properties.site_name: Burns Beach to Quinns Rock Range
properties.general_location: Between Burns Beach and Quinns Rock
properties.description: Burns Beach was used as a field firing demonstration range at least once during WWII. Most forms of artillery, armoured, and infantry weapons were employed during a demonstration in 1943.
Mitchell Plateau was a major RAAF bomber base during WWII. Records show that explosive ordnance was fired and stored in the area. High explosive ordnance was buried near the airfield on its closure.

This inner area of Learmonth Air Weapons Range used for high explosive bombing and rocket facility. Completely out of bounds to all Defence and civilian personnel unless authorised entry and accompanied by EOD technicians.

properties.general_location: 80 km W S W of Fitzroy Crossing
properties.description: Airfield  infrastructure RAAF/Allied bombers including high explosive ordnance. Possible bombing training conducted in region and  live firing training conducted by army heavy and light anti aircraft artillery.  Possible that UXO was buried on site.

properties.general_location: 8 km S S E of Rockingham
properties.description: During WWII, Warnbro was the most regularly used artillery range, resulting in severe UXO contamination. In 1959 residential development commenced without any UXO searches. Many forms of unexploded ordnance remain undisturbed requiring remediation.
The RAN has reported the presence of unexploded depth charges the stated sites. These UXO are stated as lying within 0.5 nautical miles (0.92 km) of the stated locations.

Reports refer to Smugglers Cove being used as an anti-tank range. Anti-tank ammunition in use during WWII. Possibility that artillery training, using high explosive shells, took place in the area, with the dune areas being used as targets.
The RAN has reported the presence of unexploded depth charges the stated sites. These UXO are stated as lying within 0.5 nautical miles (0.92 km) of the stated locations.
Reports of anti-aircraft battery firing seaward. Any UXO from such firings should lie on the seabed.

High explosive ordnance was fired, dropped and stored in the area during WWII.  Site assessment conducted in late 2000s found minor ordnance related debris such as fired small arms and 20mm casings, no buried or explosive material was found.
The RAN has reported the presence of unexploded depth charges the stated sites. These UXO are stated as lying within 0.5 nautical miles (0.92 km) of the stated locations.

properties.general_location: 8 km S S E of Rockingham
properties.description: During WWII, Warnbro was the most regularly used artillery range, resulting in severe UXO contamination. In 1959 residential development commenced without any UXO searches. Many forms of unexploded ordnance remain undisturbed requiring remediation.

properties.general_location: 8 km S S E of Rockingham
properties.description: During WWII, Warnbro was the most regularly used artillery range, resulting in severe UXO contamination. However, subdivision or development within this area has been searched for UXO to an acceptable level.

properties.alternative_name: Yanchep Training Area & Artillery Range Edgars Rng
properties.general_location: Between Moore River & Yanchep & 15 km Inland
properties.description: Since WWII, this area has been used as a target area by Armed forces and Allies. However, an extensive UXO survey has been undertaken and northern half out of critical area.
RAN suspects some form of mines and/or UXO at the site, and has deemed the area unsafe for anchoring, trawling or bottoming submarines.

properties.alternative_name: Walcott Field Truscott Air field Truscott Air Base
properties.description: RAAF base Truscott constructed 1943 as an advance operational base.  Extensive storage of high explosive bombs and signs of airfield being used as bombing target.

RAAF aircraft based at the airport conducted practice-bombing exercises and stored explosive ordnance. Army anti-aircraft artillery fired live shells during training exercises. During 1942, the Japanese Air Force twice bombed the airfield.

properties.general_location: 8 km S S E of Rockingham
properties.description: During WWII, Warnbro was the most regularly used artillery range, resulting in severe UXO contamination. In 1959 residential development commenced without any UXO searches. Many forms of unexploded ordnance remain undisturbed requiring remediation.

properties.general_location: 8 km S S E of Rockingham
properties.description: During WWII, Warnbro was the most regularly used artillery range, resulting in severe UXO contamination. In 1959 residential development commenced without any UXO searches. Many forms of unexploded ordnance remain undisturbed requiring remediation.

During WWII a RAAF advanced operational base was established at Carnarvon. High explosive ordnance was stored at this base and aircraft using similar ordnance are believed to have bombed land-based targets in the vicinity.

Airfield of a size sufficient to accommodate heavy bomber aircraft. It should be noted that at similar facilities, used by Allied Air Force elements during WWII, high explosive ammunition was both stored and used.

properties.alternative_name: Potshot & Learmonth RAAF Base Bombing Range
properties.description: In mid 1960s reports indicate possibility of RAAF using area as a high explosive bombing range. Large quantities of ammunition stored in caves to the west of Learmonth airbase were located and destroyed.

properties.alternative_name: Potshot & Learmonth RAAF Base Bombing Range
properties.description: During WW11 was a major Allied base where high explosive ordnance were stored and fired. Japanese Air force bombed area in 1943. Army anti-aircraft artillery conducted training and operational live firing exercises.

properties.alternative_name: Potshot & Learmonth RAAF Base Bombing Range
properties.description: Air Forces dropped bombs in the Rough Range area during WWII. United States Navy lost two depth charges in the Bay of Rest area and RAAF crews using 18 pound artillery guns fired on both land and sea targets.
Unexploded depth charges were buried at sea off Bessiers Island with a mariners note confirming occurrence.

Large amounts of explosive ordnance stored during WWII. Used as live firing training area between 1945-1950s. Since 1980 site used as defence force explosive ordnance storage facility and operates as a major RAN base.

properties.general_location: Centred 19 km N N E of Lancelin
properties.description: Numerous UXO located in area including high explosive or other munitions, as well as WWII mortar and inert projectiles especially east of Indian Ocean Drive.
Used by US Navy briefly during 1944, practice mortar located during UXO assessment.

properties.alternative_name: RAAF Pearce Bombing Range Muchea Training Area
properties.description: RAAF base since 1939 and expect that all manner of RAAF high explosives have been used on ranges.

properties.alternative_name: Yanchep Training Area & Artillery Range Edgars Rng
properties.general_location: Between Moore River & Yanchep & 8 km Inland
properties.description: Since WWII, this area has been used as a target area by Armed forces and Allies, including use of high explosive bombs/shells from aircraft, naval vessels and Army artillery, armour and infantry ammunition.
Dumping of explosive ordnance in waters around area, naval gunnery and air force bombing also undertaken during WWII.

Ocean adjacent to Perth metropolitan area has been used as live firing ranges and dumping grounds for most forms of high explosive and other ordnance used by the military over the past 100 years.  Ordnance will safely decompose if left undisturbed.

properties.general_location: Ocean North and North West of Rottnest Island
properties.description: Waters off Rottnest Island were used as a dumping ground for bulk quantities of high explosive ordnance up to the mid 1980s. The exact locations of these dumping sites have not yet been identified.
